DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain encompasses theoretical accounts from conservative and communitarian
thinkers who diagnose tradition breakdown as a central problem of modernity.
Conservative thinkers from Burke through Scruton emphasize the organic, inherited
nature of traditions and diagnose their erosion through rationalist reform,
revolutionary disruption, and liberal abstraction. Communitarian critics like
MacIntyre, Sandel, and Taylor focus on how liberal individualism and procedural
neutrality undermine the constitutive communities and shared narratives necessary
for tradition maintenance. MacIntyre's influential After Virtue traces moral
fragmentation to the Enlightenment project's abandonment of Aristotelian teleology
and tradition-constituted rationality. These thinkers offer rich phenomenological
accounts of how traditions fail: through forgetting of origins, severance from
practice, loss of authoritative narratives, and the displacement of substantive
goods by procedural frameworks.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is essential for understanding normative diagnoses of tradition
breakdown. Unlike descriptive sociological accounts, these thinkers take tradition
seriously as a philosophical category and offer sustained arguments about what is
lost when traditions fail. Their work identifies specific mechanisms: Burke's
critique of rationalist reform destroying accumulated wisdom; MacIntyre's account
of how liberal individualism severs the narrative unity necessary for virtue;
Taylor's analysis of authenticity's devolution into shallow self-fulfillment;
communitarian critiques of neutrality as itself a tradition-eroding stance.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Most of this literature focuses on Western liberal modernity. Less attention to
non-Western conservative traditions or to internal conservative debates about which
traditions deserve preservation. Limited engagement with empirical questions about
actual mechanisms of breakdown vs. philosophical claims about what ought to be
preserved.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Distinguish between: (1) Burkean conservative emphasis on organic growth vs.
revolutionary rupture; (2) MacIntyrean focus on narrative unity and practice;
(3) communitarian emphasis on constitutive communities vs. liberal atomism;
(4) Taylor's phenomenology of authenticity and moral sources. Note tensions
between universalist natural law conservatives and particularist tradition-
dependent conservatives. Consider how these diagnoses might apply beyond the
liberal-communitarian debate.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Burkean conservatism (5 papers): Organic tradition vs. rationalist reform
- MacIntyrean virtue ethics (6 papers): Tradition-constituted rationality vs. liberal individualism
- Communitarian critique (4 papers): Constitutive communities vs. liberal neutrality
- Conservative cultural criticism (3 papers): Cultural decay and loss of shared standards
====================================================================
