  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  address = {Cambridge},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Rawls's liberalism presupposes an unencumbered self prior to its ends, but selves are constituted by communal attachments and identities. Justice as fairness requires a conception of the person as freely choosing rational agent, but this atomistic view cannot account for constitutive communities, shared meanings, or narrative identity. Procedural liberalism's neutrality among conceptions of the good undermines the substantive communities necessary for meaningful choice.

  RELEVANCE: Classic communitarian critique showing how liberal individualism conceptually severs the ties between self and community. If selves are constituted by communal attachments, then liberal neutrality doesn't protect traditions—it erodes the very ground of selfhood. Diagnosis of how procedural liberalism makes tradition maintenance impossible.

  POSITION: Communitarian critique of liberal atomism. Constitutive communities vs. voluntarist association.
  },
